<Layout title="Protect yourself" description="Scams, predatory debt collectors, and deceased identity theft — how to recognize and respond to the people who will try to take advantage of a bereaved family.">
<div class="page-hero">
  <h1>Protect yourself</h1>
  <p class="subtitle">When someone dies, their name enters public record. Within days, sometimes hours, the machinery of exploitation begins. This page helps you recognize it.</p>
</div>

<div class="card card-protection">
  <p>
    <strong>The general rule:</strong> If someone contacts you after a death and creates urgency,
    they are almost certainly the problem. Legitimate institutions do not require immediate action
    from grieving families. Anyone who demands immediate payment or an immediate decision is
    counting on your inability to think clearly.
  </p>
  <p>When in doubt: slow down. Ask for it in writing. Don't pay anything today. Talk to someone you trust first.</p>
</div>

<h2>Deceased identity theft</h2>
<p>When someone dies, their Social Security number remains in databases. Criminals use this to open credit cards, take out loans, file fraudulent tax returns, and make purchases in the deceased's name. Nobody is monitoring their credit, so it can go undetected for months.</p>

<h3>What to do</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Notify all three credit bureaus immediately.</strong> Ask them to place a "deceased alert" on the file.
    <ul>
      <li>Equifax: 1-800-685-1111</li>
      <li>Experian: 1-888-397-3742</li>
      <li>TransUnion: 1-800-680-7289</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Monitor credit reports for at least one year.</strong> Request free reports at <a href="https://annualcreditreport.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">annualcreditreport.com</a> every few months. Any post-death activity is fraudulent.</li>
  <li><strong>If you find fraud:</strong> File a report at <a href="https://identitytheft.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IdentityTheft.gov</a>, file a police report, and dispute the accounts with each institution.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Debt collectors</h2>
<p>This is the most important section on this page. <strong>You are not personally responsible for a deceased person's debts unless you were a joint account holder, co-signer, or you live in a community property state and are a surviving spouse.</strong></p>
<p>Debt collectors know that most people don't know this. They will use language designed to make you feel personally responsible. They are often wrong, or lying.</p>

<h3>What collectors will say — and what it actually means</h3>
<ul>
  <li><em>"We need to settle this account."</em> — The debt exists. It doesn't mean you personally owe it.</li>
  <li><em>"This will affect the deceased's credit."</em> — The deceased no longer has credit. This is meaningless.</li>
  <li><em>"As the [son/daughter/spouse], you're responsible."</em> — Being family is not the same as being legally liable.</li>
  <li><em>"We just need a small payment."</em> — Do not pay anything until you know whether you're legally responsible. Even a small payment can be interpreted as accepting liability.</li>
</ul>

<h3>What to do when a collector calls</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Do not agree to pay anything on the first call.</li>
  <li>Say: "Please send written documentation of this debt, including the original creditor and the legal basis for the claim."</li>
  <li>Under the Fair Debt Collection Practices Act, you have the right to request written verification. Until they provide it, they cannot legally continue collection efforts.</li>
  <li>Do not give them your personal financial information.</li>
  <li>Keep a log: date, time, caller name, company, what was said.</li>
</ol>
<p>To report abusive collection: <a href="https://consumerfinance.gov/complaint" target="_blank" rel="noopener">consumerfinance.gov/complaint</a> or your state attorney general's consumer protection division.</p>

<h2>Scams targeting bereaved families</h2>
<p>Scammers monitor public obituaries. These are the most common scams targeting grieving families:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Fake debt collectors:</strong> Someone calls claiming a debt that doesn't exist. Always request written verification. Legitimate creditors provide it. Scammers won't.</li>
  <li><strong>Delivery scams:</strong> Someone arrives claiming to deliver something the deceased ordered, demanding cash payment. The deceased didn't order it. Don't pay.</li>
  <li><strong>"We worked with your loved one" scams:</strong> Someone claims they're owed money for services. Ask for a written contract and invoice. If they can't produce one, be very skeptical.</li>
  <li><strong>Fake charities:</strong> Solicitations claiming the deceased was a supporter. Verify any charity at <a href="https://give.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">give.org</a> before donating.</li>
  <li><strong>Government impersonation:</strong> Someone claiming to be from Social Security, the IRS, or Medicare demanding payment or personal information. Government agencies communicate by mail. They do not call demanding immediate payment. Hang up.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Predatory services</h2>
<p>These are legal, but they take advantage of the bereaved:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Funeral upsells:</strong> Funeral homes are legally required (FTC Funeral Rule) to provide an itemized price list. You do not have to buy a package. You can choose individual services. You can bring your own casket or urn. You are allowed to take the price list home.</li>
  <li><strong>Overpriced estate settlement services:</strong> Some charge thousands for what amounts to making phone calls. If you're considering one, ask exactly what they'll do, what it costs, and get a sample work product before signing anything.</li>
  <li><strong>Life insurance advance companies:</strong> They buy your claim at a discount, giving you immediate cash. Insurance claims process in 30–60 days. Unless you have a desperate immediate need, wait for the insurance company.</li>
</ul>

<div class="card card-caution" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
  <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; margin: 0;">
    <strong>This page provides general information, not legal advice.</strong> Laws vary by state.
    If you're unsure whether you're legally responsible for a debt, or whether a contact is
    legitimate, consult an attorney or contact your state attorney general's consumer protection division.
  </p>
</div>
